st.markdown("""
<div class="info-box">
    <b>Semantic similarity</b> — cosine similarity between the embedding of
    the generated answer and the embedding of a short reference answer,
    using the same all-MiniLM-L6-v2 model already used for retrieval. For
    out-of-scope questions, the reference is the ideal refusal text, so a
    system that correctly declines to answer scores well here too.<br><br>
    <b>Retrieval precision</b> — of the k chunks retrieved, what fraction
    came from a page actually containing the answer.<br><br>
    <b>Retrieval recall</b> — of all the correct page(s), what fraction
    were retrieved at all.<br><br>
    <b>MRR (Mean Reciprocal Rank)</b> — how high up the retrieved list the
    first correct page appeared. A correct page retrieved first scores 1.0;
    second position scores 0.5; not retrieved at all scores 0.<br><br>
    None of these four metrics make an LLM API call — they're computed
    entirely from the embedding model and the retrieval system's own
    output, so they carry no rate-limit or quota risk and can be re-run
    freely.
</div>
